            "name": "CJPC",
            "desc": "Catholic Justice and Peace Commission.",
            "content": "Headed by a moderator appointed by the chaplain with help of the parish executive. The moderator is also a member of the parish executive.\r\n\r\n<strong>Committee Composition:</strong>\r\n\r\n- The committee moderator\r\n- Two representatives from each SCC (one male, one female)\r\n- PPC representatives for YCS, Prolife and Ushers\r\n\r\n<strong>Objectives:</strong>\r\n\r\n1. To create awareness of trending issues in society.\r\n1. To ensure newly elected CJPC representatives are trained and equipped to be ambassadors of justice and peace.\r\n1. To advise, encourage and work with other groups involved in justice and peace.\r\n1. To cooperate with other institutions, churches and peoples in the spirit of Christian unity.\r\n\r\n<strong>Annual Events Organised by CJPC:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>1. First Aid Training</strong>\r\n\r\nAll CJPC members are first aid club members by default. Every academic year, the committee works with the First Aid Club to organise first aid training for all parishioners — covering basics such as assisting someone who has fainted, helping with bleeding, and road/accident first aid.\r\n\r\n<strong>2. Parish Workshop</strong>\r\n\r\nA speaker is invited to talk to and motivate parishioners on trending issues in society. Past topics have included managing stress.\r\n\r\n<strong>3. Parish Charity Work</strong>\r\n\r\nThe church joins the needy in society. In 2018/2019, about 200 parishioners attended a street families event at Mlango Kubwa in Mathare — worshipping together, teaching English/Kiswahili/Maths, playing, grooming, cooking, and eating with them.\r\n\r\n<strong>4. CJPC Training</strong>\r\n\r\nA CJPC leader from the diocese is invited to train newly elected members.\r\n\r\n<strong>5. Lenten Campaign</strong>\r\n\r\nEach year, the Kenya Conference of Catholic Bishops (KCCB) writes a book on social issues, and CJPC mobilises parishioners around its themes."
